<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-631-334  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 631 334.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  July 2 1990 n597 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hardware-software fix for Hubble? (Hubble Space Telescope)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doherty, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>NASA scientists now believe a combination of physical manipulationand software modification may alleviate the aberration in theHubble Space Telescope's mirror to an extent.andP;  NASA officials arestill uncertain whether the deformity lies in the primary orsecondary mirror, and it may be two separate flaws.andP;  Nasacomputers will use the characteristics of the flaws to model aminimal deformation mode of operation.andP;  If feasible, the mainmirror's stepper motor deflectors would be used to bow out thedistortions.andP;  Even this correction may not enable the instrumentto provide any better image resolution than is already achievableat the best earth-based observatories.andP;  NASA has also launched afull-scale investigation into the Hubble's design, manufacture,handling, and installation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Space ExplorationAstronomyDefectsHubble Space Telescope.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>